{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506171","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506171"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:41:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:41:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2529"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2529","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2529"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.17,0.16,0.39,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2529"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52940"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2529","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2529"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2529"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38335"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"377"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5317"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2416"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2419"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11294"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13433"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52940"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic after being recently diagnosed with oestrogen receptor (ER) positive breast cancer with no evidence of metastases. A core biopsy revealed the proliferation of cells that invades the basement membrane. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. There is no significant family history. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She is to be commenced on tamoxifen.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most common adverse effect of tamoxifen that this patient may experience?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Deep vein thrombosis","Osteoporosis","Vaginal dryness","Hot flushes","Dilated cardiomyopathy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETamoxifen is an oestrogen receptor modulator used in the treatment of oestrogen receptor-positive breast cancer. While it has several potential side effects, \u003Cstrong\u003Ehot flushes\u003C/strong\u003E are one of the most common. These vasomotor symptoms can significantly impact quality of life but are not typically dangerous.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeep vein thrombosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a serious potential side effect of tamoxifen. The medication increases the risk of thromboembolic events, including DVT and pulmonary embolism. However, while this risk is important to consider, it is not as common as hot flushes. Tamoxifen is contraindicated in women with a history of thrombosis or those being treated with warfarin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteoporosis\u003C/strong\u003E is actually not a side effect of tamoxifen. In fact, tamoxifen has a protective effect against osteoporosis in postmenopausal women due to its partial oestrogen agonist effects on bone. In premenopausal women, it may slightly decrease bone density, but not to the extent of causing osteoporosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaginal dryness\u003C/strong\u003E can occur with tamoxifen use, but it is less common than hot flushes. This side effect is more typically associated with aromatase inhibitors, which are used in postmenopausal women with breast cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDilated cardiomyopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is not a known side effect of tamoxifen. This cardiotoxic effect is associated with certain chemotherapy agents, particularly trastuzumab (Herceptin), which is used in HER2-positive breast cancers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther potential side effects of tamoxifen include increased risk of endometrial cancer (in postmenopausal women), mood swings, and fatigue. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hot flushes are the most common side effect of tamoxifen, affecting up to 80% of women.","Tamoxifen increases the risk of thrombosis and is contraindicated in women with a history of thrombosis or being treated with warfarin."],"references":["Smith IE, Dowsett M. Aromatase inhibitors in breast cancer. N Engl J Med 2003; 348:2431","Garber JE, Halabi S, Tolaney SM, et al. Factor V Leiden mutation and thromboembolism risk in women receiving adjuvant tamoxifen for breast cancer. J Natl Cancer Inst 2010; 102:942","Davies C, Pan H, Godwin J, et al. Long-term effects of continuing adjuvant tamoxifen to 10 years versus stopping at 5 years after diagnosis of oestrogen receptor-positive breast cancer: ATLAS, a randomised trial. Lancet 2013; 381:805","EviQ. Breast adjuvant tamoxifen. 2019. Available from: https://www.eviq.org.au/medical-oncology/breast/neoadjuvant-adjuvant/32-breast-adjuvant-tamoxifen"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38335"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2529"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38335","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38335"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-13T11:53:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-13T11:54:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2529"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52940"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":